\begin_layout Standard
Before continuing, we set a reference Markov measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 We assume this measure admits a family of bridge measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{x,y}$
\end_inset

 that are defined everywhere, and the transition kernels of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are absolutely continuous with respect to the Lebesgue measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Then, by the Radon-Nikodym theorem and the usual assumptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nikodym-1930"

\end_inset

, we can define the transition density 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(\cdot,t\mid x,s\right):=dr\left(\cdot,t\mid x,s\right)/dy$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r\left(\cdot,t\mid x,s\right)=\mathbb{P}\left(X_{t}\in\cdot\mid X_{s}=x\right)=\int_{X_{t}^{-1}\left(\cdot\right)}d\mathbb{P}\left(\cdot\mid X_{s}=x\right)=\int_{dx}
\]

\end_inset

, with the backwards transition density similarly defined.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then, we can also write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{0}\left(dx\right)=r_{0}\left(x\right)dx$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{0}\left(x\right)=\int r^{*}\left(y,1\mid x,0\right)\mathbb{R}_{1}\left(dy\right)$
\end_inset

 is the density of the marginal measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}_{0}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the Lebesgue measure, and define the density 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{1}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

